The query from that old test:

```sparql 
prefix ex:  http://www.example.org/schema#
prefix in:  http://www.example.org/instance#

select ?x where {
  graph ?g {
    {
      select ?x where { ?x ?p ?g }
    }
  }
}

```

I'm actually thinking that it's a variable scoping issue.

```sparql
prefix ex:  http://www.example.org/schema#
prefix in:  http://www.example.org/instance#

select ?x where {
  graph ?g {
    {
      select ?x where { ?x ?p ?g }
    }
  }
}
```

Since SPARQL has bottom-up semantics the inner SELECT query should be executed without knowledge of the outer variables. It's only when the results from the SELECT query bubble up that they get "filtered" by any variables that are bound in the outer scope.

Since `?g` isn't declared in the projection of the inner SELECT query then it should not be affected by the outer `?g` bound to the named graph.

Consider the following query:

```sparql
prefix ex:  http://www.example.org/schema#
prefix in:  http://www.example.org/instance#

select ?x ?a ?b ?c where {
  graph ?g {
    {
      select ?x ?g where { ?x ?p ?g }
    }
    ?a ?b ?c.
  }
}
```

Here the inner SELECT produces results for both `?x` and `?g`. The outer `?g` in the graph declaration will be bound by the bindings from the inner SELECT, which in turn will affect the `?a ?b ?c.` line.

If we remove `?g` from the projection of the inner SELECT:

```sparql
prefix ex:  http://www.example.org/schema#
prefix in:  http://www.example.org/instance#

select ?x ?a ?b ?c where {
  graph ?g {
    {
      select ?x where { ?x ?p ?g }
    }
    ?a ?b ?c.
  }
}
```

Then now the `graph ?g` declaration is unbound. Se we would return results for `?a ?b ?c` from all graphs without being affect by the `?g` within the inner SELECT.

The reason seems to be this condition in `MemoryOverflowModel`:

```java
	// Sync if either the estimated size of the next block is larger than remaining memory, or
	// if less than 15% of the heap is still free (this last condition to avoid GC overhead limit)
	if (freeToAllocateMemory < MIN_AVAILABLE_MEM_BEFORE_OVERFLOWING ||
			freeToAllocateMemory < Math.min(0.15 * maxMemory, maxBlockSize)) {
		logger.debug("syncing at {} triples. max block size: {}", size, maxBlockSize);
		overflowToDisk();
	}
```

If, for example, `Math.max(0.3 * maxMemory, maxBlockSize)` is used then syncing to disk works as expected:
